/*****************************************************************************
    bytecode — incant-side bytecode dispatch and (eventually) emitter actions.

    Phase 2 step 4: interpret(). Walks a bytecoded action body's member
    instructions, dispatching each through its op's `interpret` sub-attribute.

    Dispatch idiom (per design Q1 + the single-method-per-field rule):
        handler = grup.interpret;       // resolve interpret sub-attribute
        result  = handler(grup);        // call its method (runX in Bytecode.mm)

    Successor convention (Q3 — implicit-next):
        result == null   → for-loop's natural next-member step (fall through)
        result != null   → branch override; reassign grup, for-loop advances
                           from there next iteration

    The for-loop-as-while trick: `for grup in body; members` is C-equivalent
    to `while grup = body.nextMember(grup);`. Reassigning grup mid-loop
    (when a handler returns a branch target) transparently redirects the
    next iteration's nextMember() lookup. This is also how labels work:
    when an emitted body contains label sentinels, a branch can target a
    label and the for-loop's natural "next sibling" advance from the label
    lands on the actual continuation instruction — no special label-skip
    logic needed.

    Loop end is the natural one — body.nextMember(grup) returns null after
    the last instruction (runRET, by emitter convention, sits there).
*****************************************************************************/
register(Bytecoding);
define
    interpret body; {
        for grup in body; members
            handler = grup.interpret;
            if !handler;
                print "interpret: no handler for" grup.taG:;
                return;
            result = handler(grup);
            if result;  grup = result;
        }
    ;
